model PlaybookProgress {
  id             Int      @id @default(autoincrement())
  dealId         Int
  playbookId     Int
  completedSteps String?  @db.Text // JSON array of step indices
  tenantId       Int      @default(1)
  tenant         Tenant   @relation(fields: [tenantId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  createdAt      DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt      DateTime @updatedAt

  /// One progress row per (tenant, deal, playbook). A deal can run multiple playbooks in parallel, but a given playbook against a given deal has exactly one progress record (resuming updates the row). tenantId is keyed defensively even though Deal is tenant-scoped and dealId is globally unique under autoincrement — guards against future id-allocation changes (UUIDs, per-tenant sharding) where dealId might collide across tenants. The application code in routes/playbooks.js already passes tenantId in every where-clause, so this is also a structural alignment between schema + queries. Audit decision after the v3.4.6 #413 batch 2 deferral; the original "tenantId implicit via dealId" claim was load-bearing only on the autoincrement assumption.
  /// Migration safety: replacing `@@unique([dealId, playbookId])` with the new key is strictly more permissive (every prior unique pair is still unique under the new constraint), so backfill is unnecessary and no duplicate-row check is needed before the migration runs. Blessed via [allow-unique] in the introducing commit message.
  @@unique([tenantId, dealId, playbookId])
}

